00:14:14,416 --> 00:14:18,001
and the American people that
we are capable of more than stagnation.

228
00:14:18,002 --> 00:14:21,296
And that's worth something,
even if it hurts.

229
00:14:23,756 --> 00:14:25,842
Who can I count on?

230
00:14:46,525 --> 00:14:48,317
Copy that.

231
00:14:56,073 --> 00:14:59,576
The fact that there's still
a door between us, I take as a bad sign.

232
00:14:59,577 --> 00:15:01,993
One tested negative,
one inconclusive, sir.

233
00:15:01,994 --> 00:15:04,120
That means we have to take
the samples to the lab.

234
00:15:04,121 --> 00:15:06,955
- So how much longer?
- Another three or four hours.

235
00:15:06,956 --> 00:15:10,792
We have an important vote going to the
floor. I have to be talking to my people.

236
00:15:10,793 --> 00:15:14,545
The vote is delayed, sir.
We're evacuating this side of the Capitol.

237
00:15:14,546 --> 00:15:17,547
- So no vote?
- Not until we get the all-clear.

238
00:15:17,548 --> 00:15:20,508
- Good things happen to good people.
- Another thing, sir.

239
00:15:20,509 --> 00:15:24,636
All cell phone service, WiFi,
land lines, we'll be blocking them,

240
00:15:24,637 --> 00:15:26,804
in case there's
a legitimate security threat.

241
00:15:26,806 --> 00:15:30,307
- I need to be able to call my wife!
- I apologize, sir.

242
00:15:30,308 --> 00:15:33,476
- We can have someone notify her.
- No, it needs to be me.

243
00:15:33,477 --> 00:15:35,854
She gets very anxious
if she doesn't recognize the voice.

244
00:15:35,855 --> 00:15:37,979
Congressman, I have
strict instructions not...

245
00:15:37,980 --> 00:15:40,816
Figure it out, unless you want me
to get the White House involved.

246
00:15:42,818 --> 00:15:44,528
I'll find a way, sir.

247
00:15:45,945 --> 00:15:49,365
There are advantages
to being vice president.

248
00:15:52,659 --> 00:15:56,494
Ma'am, we'll have to ask you
to remain up here for a little while.

249
00:15:56,495 --> 00:15:59,246
- Is it the quarantine?
- The Capitol is being evacuated.

250
00:15:59,247 --> 00:16:04,125
We expect everything to be fine.
It's just standard procedure.

251
00:16:04,126 --> 00:16:07,086
You won't be able to get through.
Communication's being jammed.

252
00:16:07,087 --> 00:16:10,213
- You mean I can't even speak to Francis?
- Not until the all-clear.

253
00:16:10,214 --> 00:16:12,882
- How long?
- - Four hours is the estimate right now.

254
00:16:12,883 --> 00:16:16,636
- We're supposed to tape in 25 minutes.
- - Nothing we can do.

255
00:16:16,637 --> 00:16:20,639
- You OK?
- Yes.

256
00:16:20,640 --> 00:16:23,350
I'll go talk to Emma.

257
00:16:24,477 --> 00:16:26,686
No, I'm fine. Thank you.

258
00:16:30,105 --> 00:16:33,273
Em.

259
00:16:33,274 --> 00:16:35,733
- So we might have a problem.
- It's all over the news.

260
00:16:35,734 --> 00:16:38,610
- Yeah, it could be a while.
- Can we get audio from the vice president?

261
00:16:38,612 --> 00:16:41,363
Communications are being
jammed until the evacuation's over.

262
00:16:41,364 --> 00:16:42,864
- Have you spoken to Ashleigh?
- She thinks we should get

263
00:16:42,865 --> 00:16:44,491
a sat truck down here
and wait and go live.

264
00:16:44,492 --> 00:16:46,700
I can't guarantee
when that'll be.

265
00:16:46,701 --> 00:16:49,495
The vice president is quarantined
in the Capitol and we have an exclusive.

266
00:16:49,496 --> 00:16:51,913
The network will broadcast
whenever the hell we tell them to.

267
00:16:51,914 --> 00:16:54,123
<i>They're</i>
<i>holding off until you get here.</i>

268
00:16:54,124 --> 00:16:56,374
You should do the
interview solo.

269
00:16:56,375 --> 00:16:59,710
<i>- I'd rather wait.</i>
- Who knows whether we'll win the vote?

270
00:16:59,711 --> 00:17:02,212
If we lose, I don't want my face
on national television.

271
00:17:02,213 --> 00:17:05,423
- This could be a silver lining.
- <i> I don't know, Francis.</i>

272
00:17:05,424 --> 00:17:08,926
- I'm sure you'll be terrific.
- <i> Let me run it past Connor.</i>

273
00:17:08,927 --> 00:17:11,261
OK.
Thank you, we're done.

274
00:17:11,262 --> 00:17:16,265
- Sir, we were able to get Mrs. Blythe.
- Donald.

275
00:17:16,266 --> 00:17:18,308
- Marjory?
<i>- Hello?</i>

276
00:17:18,309 --> 00:17:21,519
- Yes, it's me, sweetheart.
- <i> It's hard to hear you.</i>

277
00:17:21,520 --> 00:17:25,815
- We're still stuck inside the office.
- <i> What office?</i>

278
00:17:25,816 --> 00:17:29,192
At the Capitol. It's going
to be a little while longer.

279
00:17:29,193 --> 00:17:31,652
<i>But why are you there?</i>
<i>It's Sunday.</i>

280
00:17:31,653 --> 00:17:34,613
- No, it's Friday, sweetheart.
- <i> Donald?</i>

281
00:17:34,614 --> 00:17:37,657
- I'm here.
- <i> Who is this man with me?</i>

282
00:17:37,658 --> 00:17:42,786
He's a police officer. They're using
walkie-talkies so we can speak.

283
00:17:42,787 --> 00:17:45,913
<i>- Who am I talking to?
- - It's your husband, ma'am.</i>

284
00:17:45,914 --> 00:17:49,040
<i>- I'm not married.</i>
- It's me. It's Donald.

285
00:17:49,041 --> 00:17:51,083
<i>Turn it off.</i>
<i>I don't know that man.</i>

286
00:17:51,084 --> 00:17:54,713
- Marjory!
- -<i> She went to the other room, sir.</i>

287
00:17:54,714 --> 00:17:59,799
OK, thank you.

288
00:17:59,800 --> 00:18:03,219
- If you could stay with her, please?
- -<i> Yes, sir.</i>

289
00:18:26,946 --> 00:18:28,864
Drink?

290
00:18:31,575 --> 00:18:34,701
Sure. Why not?

291
00:18:34,702 --> 00:18:37,453
For all we know, it could be
midnight before he's out.

292
00:18:37,454 --> 00:18:39,748
- He still needs to manage the vote.
- - We're fine if it's 2am.

293
00:18:39,749 --> 00:18:41,957
When everyone's asleep.

294
00:18:41,958 --> 00:18:44,000
- People would stay up for this.
- The whole point was primetime.

295
00:18:44,001 --> 00:18:45,752
- Then we do it tomorrow.
- We've already set aside

296
00:18:45,753 --> 00:18:47,293
half a day for this.
The vice president can't

297
00:18:47,294 --> 00:18:49,337
rearrange his schedule
for an interview.

298
00:18:49,339 --> 00:18:52,799
- I don't see any other options.
- I spoke to Francis over the radio.

299
00:18:52,800 --> 00:18:57,469
- We think I should do it alone.
- Just you?

300
00:18:57,470 --> 00:18:59,596
Mrs. Underwood and Ashleigh,
one-on-one.

301
00:18:59,597 --> 00:19:01,056
Maybe we can
broadcast his voice...

302
00:19:01,057 --> 00:19:03,223
Francis doesn't want
the entire interview

303
00:19:03,224 --> 00:19:04,975
to be about the quarantine.

304
00:19:04,976 --> 00:19:07,142
Neither do I.
That's just spectacle.

305
00:19:07,143 --> 00:19:09,020
The quarantine is news.
We have an opportunity...

306
00:19:09,021 --> 00:19:11,230
- We're done.
- What?

307
00:19:11,231 --> 00:19:13,356
- Cancel the interview. No reschedule.
- Come on.

308
00:19:13,357 --> 00:19:16,652
Please, pack up
everything and leave.

309
00:19:17,486 --> 00:19:20,404
OK, let me call Ashleigh.

310
00:19:22,573 --> 00:19:28,077
I thought I'd get used to it,
but no. Hurts every time.

311
00:19:28,078 --> 00:19:32,747
You spend 30 years with someone and then
they don't have a damn clue who you are.

312
00:19:35,458 --> 00:19:38,292
Oh... I really shouldn't.

313
00:19:38,293 --> 00:19:40,294
If we never did anything
we shouldn't do,

314
00:19:40,295 --> 00:19:42,964
we'd never feel good
about doing the things we should.

315
00:19:42,965 --> 00:19:46,632
- Excellent point.
- If these are our last moments on Earth,

316
00:19:46,633 --> 00:19:49,551
I don't know about you,
but I'd rather go out with a buzz on.

317
00:19:49,552 --> 00:19:53,097
To Marjory.

318
00:19:53,098 --> 00:19:58,392
- You love her dearly.
- More than anything.

319
00:20:01,478 --> 00:20:05,354
I can't imagine what I'd do
without Claire, or if she...

320
00:20:05,355 --> 00:20:07,732
...didn't remember who I was.

321
00:20:07,733 --> 00:20:10,525
- Hopefully you'll never have to.
- It makes me angry that you do.

322
00:20:10,526 --> 00:20:14,155
- That anybody does. - No sense being
angry over what you can't change.

323
00:20:15,530 --> 00:20:19,117
How much funding
does Alzheimer's research get?

324
00:20:19,118 --> 00:20:21,785
Just under 500 million.

325
00:20:21,786 --> 00:20:24,829
Well, I'm no expert, but that
sounds inadequate to me.

326
00:20:24,830 --> 00:20:29,040
It is. For every $100
we allocate to research,

327
00:20:29,041 --> 00:20:33,127
- we spend nearly $30,000 on care.
- We oughta change that.

328
00:20:33,128 --> 00:20:35,879
I tried. My bill didn't even
leave committee.

329
00:20:35,880 --> 00:20:39,256
- Who opposed it?
- Howard Webb.

330
00:20:39,257 --> 00:20:43,760
- Appropriations.
- He didn't even put it to a vote.

331
00:20:43,761 --> 00:20:48,263
- I've never been fond of Howard.
- That makes two of us.

332
00:20:48,264 --> 00:20:51,683
- What was his argument?
- He didn't feel he owed me one.

333
00:20:51,684 --> 00:20:54,727
"Fiscally irresponsible,"
is all he said.

334
00:20:54,728 --> 00:21:00,900
Walk me through the
specifics of your bill.

335
00:21:06,696 --> 00:21:10,948
- I see what you're doing.
- Doing what?

336
00:21:10,949 --> 00:21:13,240
- You're disgusting, Frank.
- Excuse me.

337
00:21:13,241 --> 00:21:15,952
- Using my wife.
- Donald, what are you saying?

338
00:21:15,953 --> 00:21:19,579
You think I'll give in on entitlement
if you slap some extra Alzheimer's funding

339
00:21:19,580 --> 00:21:21,873
- on the table?
- I was not suggesting that at all.

340
00:21:21,874 --> 00:21:25,167
- Bullshit, Frank.
- You think as little of me as you want,

341
00:21:25,168 --> 00:21:26,877
but I do not barter
with people's health.

342
00:21:26,878 --> 00:21:29,420
Then why are you trying to raise
the age of retirement?

343
00:21:29,421 --> 00:21:32,255
Medical research we can afford.
Medicare we can't.

344
00:21:32,256 --> 00:21:36,134
- There are realities, Donald.
- Don't talk down to me about realities.

345
00:21:36,135 --> 00:21:39,137
My wife is dying!
That's a reality!

346
00:21:39,138 --> 00:21:42,556
Other people will die, too,
if your package succeeds!

347
00:21:42,557 --> 00:21:46,017
That's a reality! Goddamn it,
I wish I wasn't stuck

348
00:21:46,018 --> 00:21:48,309
- in this fucking room with you!
- Donald.

349
00:21:48,310 --> 00:21:50,312
I'm done talking!

350
00:21:52,023 --> 00:21:53,982
- One more time.
- I've got it.

351
00:21:53,983 --> 00:21:56,482
I want it to sound more natural.

352
00:21:56,484 --> 00:21:59,861
Francis and I wanted to devote
our lives to public service.

353
00:21:59,862 --> 00:22:04,657
And we didn't feel that we could both
do that and be the parents we wanted to be.

354
00:22:04,658 --> 00:22:07,283
And by making that choice,
it allows more time for us

355
00:22:07,284 --> 00:22:09,952
- to be in the service of others.
- Good, that sounds good.

356
00:22:09,953 --> 00:22:12,329
We need you,
Mrs. Underwood.

357
00:22:18,168 --> 00:22:21,753
Keep Derek at the Capitol. I want quotes
from evacuees and Homeland Security.

358
00:22:21,754 --> 00:22:25,590
And Sarah should be finishing
that history of biohazard scares.

359
00:22:25,591 --> 00:22:28,050
I'll be there soon.

360
00:22:28,051 --> 00:22:30,969
- I have to go.
- No. We're not done yet.

361
00:22:30,970 --> 00:22:33,596
This is a major story.
I'll come back tomorrow.

362
00:22:33,597 --> 00:22:36,472
Come here two days in a row
and this is how patterns emerge.

363
00:22:36,473 --> 00:22:40,267
The FBI likes patterns. And we do not
give the FBI what the FBI likes.

364
00:22:40,268 --> 00:22:42,228
I can't disappear all
day in the middle of...

365
00:22:42,229 --> 00:22:47,231
- I have eight reporters out in the field.
- Stop!

366
00:22:47,232 --> 00:22:52,569
- Tell me why I purchased Cashew.
- I don't know.

367
00:22:52,570 --> 00:22:55,654
Companionship?

368
00:22:55,655 --> 00:22:57,364
Yes.

369
00:22:59,158 --> 00:23:02,534
But more importantly,
a reminder that I am never more

370
00:23:02,535 --> 00:23:06,705
than one wrong move away
from life in a cage.

371
00:23:06,706 --> 00:23:08,497
You stay.

372
00:23:08,498 --> 00:23:10,792
I'm gonna walk you through every
line of code I intend to write,

373
00:23:10,793 --> 00:23:13,585
every attempt I make to breach
the wall. If we get caught,

374
00:23:13,586 --> 00:23:16,212
you don't get to plead
ignorance. We go down together.

375
00:23:16,213 --> 00:23:19,672
I didn't sign up for Bonnie and Clyde.
You need me for this one thing.

376
00:23:19,673 --> 00:23:22,300
Just like I need you.
But whatever you've done before me...

377
00:23:24,595 --> 00:23:28,723
You know where I live,
and you know who I am.

378
00:23:34,560 --> 00:23:38,606
Sit down. The sooner we start,
the sooner we finish.

379
00:23:43,109 --> 00:23:46,736
<i>The Capitol is still on lockdown</i>
<i>as hazmat crews continue</i>

380
00:23:46,737 --> 00:23:48,446
<i>a thorough sweep</i>
<i>of the building.</i>

381
00:23:48,447 --> 00:23:50,489
<i>Earlier this morning,</i>
<i>a white powder-like</i>

382
00:23:50,490 --> 00:23:52,741
<i>- substance was found</i>
<i>in a package...</i>

383
00:23:52,742 --> 00:23:55,660
<i>...mailed to the office of</i>
<i>Majority Whip Jacqueline Sharp.</i>

384
00:23:55,661 --> 00:23:59,079
- Are we free to go?
- Almost, sir. Less than an hour.

385
00:23:59,080 --> 00:24:02,123
- I've got a message from your wife.
- - What is it?

386
00:24:02,124 --> 00:24:04,625
She's doing the
interview live, right now.

387
00:24:04,626 --> 00:24:08,795
<i>...Congressman Donald Blythe and 14 of Ms.
Sharp's staff.</i>

388
00:24:08,796 --> 00:24:13,507
<i>Mrs. Underwood, I so appreciate</i>
<i>you taking the time to speak with us today</i>

389
00:24:13,508 --> 00:24:17,510
<i>in what I am certain</i>
<i>is a very stressful situation.</i>

390
00:24:17,511 --> 00:24:21,263
<i>- Thank you, Ashleigh.</i>
<i>- Have you spoken with your husband today?</i>

391
00:24:21,264 --> 00:24:24,473
<i>Yes, I did,</i>
<i>and he's in very good spirits,</i>

392
00:24:24,474 --> 00:24:26,558
<i>and in good hands</i>
<i>with the Secret Service.</i>

393
00:24:26,559 --> 00:24:28,978
<i>Of course, he's very</i>
<i>disappointed he couldn't be here.</i>

394
00:24:28,979 --> 00:24:32,188
<i>Well, our thoughts are with him
and everyone else quarantined</i>

395
00:24:32,189 --> 00:24:34,023
<i>- at the Capitol today.</i>
<i>- Thank you.</i>

396
00:24:34,024 --> 00:24:37,109
I'd like to begin
with Claire Underwood

397
00:24:37,110 --> 00:24:40,320
before you met your husband,
in Texas.

398
00:24:40,321 --> 00:24:43,155
- And I have a couple of pictures.
- Oh, no.

399
00:24:43,156 --> 00:24:45,073
Yes.

400
00:24:45,074 --> 00:24:48,408
Oh, my goodness.
That was Red.

401
00:24:48,409 --> 00:24:52,745
- An accomplished rider?
- An enthusiast.

402
00:24:52,746 --> 00:24:57,415
- This one's from a couple of years later.
- Oh, my goodness.

403
00:24:57,416 --> 00:25:00,294
You like those penny loafers?
Those are won...

404
00:25:00,295 --> 00:25:05,007
Those are two very different girls.
Which one are you more comfortable being?

405
00:25:06,799 --> 00:25:11,344
My family's ranch,
that was home for me.

406
00:25:11,345 --> 00:25:13,095
You didn't like the prep school?

407
00:25:13,096 --> 00:25:16,640
No, I think
I preferred the dirt.

408
00:25:19,392 --> 00:25:23,061
You grew up in Dallas,
though. Highland Park.

409
00:25:23,062 --> 00:25:27,772
Yes. My father, well, he was
a businessman, so we lived in the city.

410
00:25:27,773 --> 00:25:32,526
But we're ranchers. I mean,
we go back three generations, our family.

411
00:25:32,527 --> 00:25:35,238
Your parents were very wealthy.

412
00:25:35,239 --> 00:25:38,198
We were comfortable, yes.

413
00:25:38,199 --> 00:25:41,367
They made sure
I wanted for nothing.

414
00:25:41,368 --> 00:25:44,078
It was a very happy childhood.

415
00:25:44,079 --> 00:25:48,497
What is your most vivid
memory from that time?

416
00:25:48,498 --> 00:25:53,002
My most vivid memory?
Wow. Um...

417
00:25:55,880 --> 00:25:58,756
Probably, when I was
about nine or ten,

418
00:25:58,757 --> 00:26:03,467
my father took me to Dealey
Plaza where Kennedy was shot.

419
00:26:03,468 --> 00:26:06,720
And he said, "Claire,
a great man died here."

420
00:26:06,721 --> 00:26:11,057
And I remember not
fully comprehending

421
00:26:11,058 --> 00:26:13,392
the meaning of death yet.

422
00:26:13,393 --> 00:26:17,938
And I asked him how he died
and he told me.

423
00:26:17,939 --> 00:26:21,608
And I remember feeling so sad,
so angry.

424
00:26:22,609 --> 00:26:25,984
It seemed so unfair.

425
00:26:25,985 --> 00:26:31,031
I started to cry, and my daddy picked
me up and he wrapped his arms around me

426
00:26:31,032 --> 00:26:34,866
and he said,
"Don't be sad, sweetheart.

427
00:26:34,867 --> 00:26:40,289
He made the world a better place,
but sometimes that comes at a price."

428
00:26:42,416 --> 00:26:45,542
I guess that was
the most vivid memory.

429
00:27:01,470 --> 00:27:04,681
- We're only eight votes away.
- I'm sorry, I made up my mind.

430
00:27:04,682 --> 00:27:06,392
Me too. I gotta stick
to my guns on this one.

431
00:27:06,393 --> 00:27:09,269
You would rather
let the government shut down...

432
00:27:09,270 --> 00:27:11,895
Don't put that on us because
we're on the ass-end of the whip list.

433
00:27:11,896 --> 00:27:14,815
Don't get us wrong.
We have a lot of respect for you, Jackie.

434
00:27:14,816 --> 00:27:18,609
You're doing a fine job since Frank's gone.
Different styles, but a fine job.

435
00:27:18,610 --> 00:27:21,946
Excuse us just a moment.

436
00:27:21,947 --> 00:27:25,906
- They're not taking me seriously.
- Because you're not Frank.

437
00:27:25,907 --> 00:27:29,701
- You mean because I'm not a man.
- No, I mean Frank.

438
00:27:29,702 --> 00:27:33,121
They're used to being offered something.
Ask them what they want.

439
00:27:33,122 --> 00:27:34,956
Paul needs help with the
waste treatment facility.

440
00:27:34,957 --> 00:27:38,250
You're being just
as condescending as they are.

441
00:27:38,251 --> 00:27:43,212
Take some good advice when you get it.
I was right earlier, wasn't I?

442
00:27:47,842 --> 00:27:52,093
Paul, Remy tells me you
need a waste treatment plant.

443
00:27:52,094 --> 00:27:56,055
We've had some trouble
getting matching federal funds.

444
00:27:56,056 --> 00:28:00,058
Ben, you mentioned once
a winery museum in your district.

445
00:28:00,059 --> 00:28:02,352
We are making some
